hich it is put. Reason has interacted with experience in a new world and a cold climate to create a distinctive Canadian community. The diversity of political, geographic, social, and religious factors has fostered a particular kind of thinking, particular ways of reasoning and communicating. Rather than one grand, overarching Canadian way of thinking, there are “many faces of reason,” “a kind of philosophic federalism”. The book has two dimensions: “it is a continuos story which makes a point about the development of philosophical reason in the Canadian context. it is a reference work which may be consulted by readers interested in particular figures, ideas, movements, or periods.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPhilosophyxHistoryxCanadaxCanada. 0aPhilosophyzCanadaxHistory. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh1 aBeaven, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlewett, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrett, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroeke, James Ten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBucke, Richard M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInnis, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrving, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeirstead, Wilfred Currier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLighthall, William D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLodge, Rupert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct